05428nam a22007935i 9780520318670DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20201989cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203186707 a10.1525/97805203186702doi  a(DE-B1597)570434  a(OCoLC)1202623141  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0030002bisacsh00aNeo-Confucian Education /ced. by John W. Chaffee, Wm. Theodore de Bary.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©1989  a1 online resource (608 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on China ;v90 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early days of the modernization of East Asia, Neo-Confucianism was often held responsible for the purported intellectual, political, and social failings of traditional societies in the nineteenth century. Today, with frequent comparisons between the rapid success at modernization of many of these societies and the slowness of other underdeveloped countries, Neo-Confucianism has come to be seen under a very different light; analysts now point to the common Confucian culture of China, Japan, Korea, and overseas Chinese communities as a driving force in the East Asian peoples' receptivity to new learning, disciplined industriousness, and capacity for both cultural and economic development. Central to this remarkable capacity for development, these essays argue, lies the influence of the great twelfth-century thinker Chu Hsi. He has been considered responsible for providing much of the intellectual mortar that preserved the established order for centuries. However, when viewed in their historical setting, many of Chu's views can be seen as liberal--indeed, progressive. This is the first comprehensive study of Chu as an educator and of the propagation of his teachings throughout East Asia. Covering a wide spectrum of intellectual and social developments, the contributors address the ways in which Neo-Confucian thought and ethics were adapted to changes in Chinese society that anticipate many features and problems of modern society today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 4aAsian history. 4aChina. 4aJapan. 4ahistory. 4amodernization. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aBary, Wm. Theodore de, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBirge, Bettine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirge, Bettine.1 aBoi, Peter K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaffee, John W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaffee, John W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChan, Wing-tsit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChu, Ron-Guey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEbrey, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHymes, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelleher, M. Theresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Thomas H. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKnight, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalton, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWei-ming, Tu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWu, Pei-yi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYu, Chün-fang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZürcher, Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 ade Baiy, Theodore, econtributor.4ctb4https: